# Using Scope

Scope is a local-first kanban for projects, epics, stories, and bugs. It ships
as a CLI and a GitHub-Projects-style web UI.

## When to use

- Multi-step task ("rebuild auth", "ship feature X") ΓÁÈ create an epic plus child stories.
- Starting a session ΓÁÈ list open tickets in the project for context.
- Finishing a piece of work ΓÁÈ mark the ticket `done`, attach the branch / PR.
- Discovering a real bug ΓÁÈ create a `bug` ticket with reproduction steps.

Skip Scope for one-off questions or trivial single-edit requests.

## How to access

Shell out to the `scope` CLI. Every command supports `--json`:

```bash
scope --json ticket list -p MA
scope --json ticket show MA-3
```

Install if needed: `brew install briannadoubt/tap/scope`

## Data model

| | |
|---|---|
| Project | top-level container, has a 2-10 letter key (`MA`) |
| Epic | high-level body of work, parent for stories/bugs |
| Story | unit of work toward an epic |
| Bug | defect, can live under an epic |
| Status | `backlog` ΓÁÈ `todo` ΓÁÈ `in_progress` ΓÁÈ `in_review` ΓÁÈ `done` (+ `cancelled`) |
| Priority | `low` / `medium` / `high` / `urgent` |
| Relations | `blocks`, `blocked_by`, `relates_to`, `duplicates`, `duplicate_of` |

## Common operations

```bash
scope init
scope project create my-app MA "My App"

scope ticket create MA "Auth refactor" -t epic -p high
scope ticket create MA "OAuth login"  -t story --parent MA-1

scope branch  MA-2 feat/oauth --in-progress
scope pr      MA-2 https://github.com/owner/repo/pull/42 --in-review
scope status  MA-2 done

scope board -p MA
scope --json ticket show MA-2
scope comment MA-2 "Token expiry was 5min; bumped to 1h" --by cursor
scope link add MA-2 blocked_by MA-7
```

## Guardrails

- Don't create projects without explicit user request.
- Don't delete tickets ΓÇõ set status to `cancelled` instead.
- Keep titles human-readable; implementation details go in the description.
- Update status as work happens, not all at once at the end.
- Use `--by <name>` so the history shows who touched what.

## Realtime + multi-agent

If the user runs `scope serve` somewhere, the web UI comes up at
`http://localhost:4321` and every `scope` CLI call pushes to all viewers via
SSE in ~100ms. **Never pass `--port`** ΓÇõ concurrent `scope serve` invocations
auto-discover the running hub. With multiple agents, **read state before
writing state** ΓÇõ last write wins on conflicting updates.

If the user previews scope from Claude Code, each project's
`.claude/launch.json` must use `scope preview --port <unique>` (not
`scope serve`) ΓÇõ `preview_start` enforces one tracked server per port, and
two projects both registering `port: 4321` stop each other across panes.
`scope preview` is a tiny per-pane reverse proxy forwarding a unique port
(4322, 4323, ...) to the shared hub.

